### The gap (why the live failure persists despite the fixes — hypothesis)
The strongest hypothesis is **scope + activation mismatch**, not that every shipped fix is absent.

For `mk-spec-memory`, the fix that should have prevented owner-disposal teardown is re-election: phase `022` added detached spawn + release-on-shutdown, phase `027` rolled it out, and current code makes it default-on unless `SPECKIT_DAEMON_REELECTION=0/off` is present. Cites: `022.../implementation-summary.md:52-60`, `027.../implementation-summary.md:51-59`, current `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:196-206`, `.opencode/bin/mk-spec-memory-launcher.cjs:1449-1470`.

The observed `mk-spec-memory` stale socket still fits if one of these is true: the live launcher was an old pre-default-on process, the process env disabled re-election, shutdown did not see `hasLiveDaemon`, the daemon died by crash/OOM/SIGKILL rather than owner-disposal release, or no fresh non-warm launcher path ran afterward to trigger the phase `019` dead-socket reap. Phase `019` heals stale sockets only when a launcher does the bridge/probe/respawn path; a warm-only CLI probe that refuses cold spawn can still report stale socket without exercising the healing path. Cites: `019.../implementation-summary.md:51-55`, live diagnosis `031.../research/live-diagnosis.md:6-14`.

For `mk-skill-advisor`, the gap is clearer: the 026/007 re-election work is documented for `mk-spec-memory`, and current `mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs` has a reconnecting session proxy but no `daemonReelectionEnabled`/release branch. Its signal handler still kills the child and clears leases. Cites: `022.../implementation-summary.md:70`, current `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1144-1182`, `.opencode/bin/mk-skill-advisor-launcher.cjs:1185-1205`. So “re-election default-on” apparently does **not** protect `mk-skill-advisor`; that daemon can still die with its launcher and leave a stale socket.

For `mk-code-index`, phase `020` should prevent hard client disconnects during owner change, but it does not promise orphan-launcher cleanup. The Stop-hook orphan sweep that would address orphan accumulation is phase `021` and remains default-off. Cites: `020.../implementation-summary.md:52-60`, `021.../implementation-summary.md:108-110`, live diagnosis `031.../research/live-diagnosis.md:8`.

Specific hypothesis: **the system has three different launcher lifecycles, but the definitive owner-disposal release/re-election behavior is only fully present in `mk-spec-memory`; `mk-skill-advisor` still follows kill-on-shutdown, and `mk-code-index` still allows launcher processes to accumulate unless default-off orphan sweeping is enabled. When this Claude session was not cleanly bridged and only warm probes were used, no cold-start/reap path necessarily ran to repair stale sockets.**

